01:21:14,374 --> 01:21:15,626
Jessica,
I need a word.

955
01:21:15,626 --> 01:21:16,210
Excuse me.

956
01:21:16,210 --> 01:21:18,420
What's the matter? Is there a problem?

957
01:21:20,506 --> 01:21:23,008
And Edward seems
really nice.

958
01:21:23,133 --> 01:21:24,968
Mom, I think I'm going to throw up.

959
01:21:25,010 --> 01:21:26,970
Just remember,
in a few minutes from now,

960
01:21:27,012 --> 01:21:29,556
the curse will be broken.

961
01:21:29,890 --> 01:21:33,727
There is no curse. The only one
cursed here is me.

962
01:21:40,734 --> 01:21:44,071
- For starters...
- Losing your eye was your own damn fault.

963
01:21:44,112 --> 01:21:46,365
- Now what?
- I just wanted to apologise.

964
01:21:46,406 --> 01:21:48,242
Apology not accepted.

965
01:21:49,368 --> 01:21:52,496
What?!
I have a wedding to go to!

966
01:21:53,330 --> 01:21:55,249
Meet Johnny Martin.

967
01:22:00,254 --> 01:22:02,631
I told you not to rush
the process.

968
01:22:02,673 --> 01:22:04,508
This doesn't change a thing.

969
01:22:04,591 --> 01:22:07,302
How can you say that?
Not only was Edward part of...

970
01:22:07,344 --> 01:22:10,514
As you yourself once said,
he's still one of our own kind.

971
01:22:10,556 --> 01:22:13,684
OK, fine. What about Max, or Johnny
or whatever his name is?

972
01:22:13,725 --> 01:22:14,268
What about him?

973
01:22:14,309 --> 01:22:16,603
Don't you think Penelope's
entitled to know?

974
01:22:16,645 --> 01:22:17,729
That he lied about everything?

975
01:22:17,771 --> 01:22:20,440
That he doesn't have the
power to break the curse.

976
01:22:20,482 --> 01:22:22,734
Why on earth would
she need to know that?

977
01:22:22,734 --> 01:22:26,530
Don't you see? Maybe that's
the only reason he said no.

978
01:22:26,905 --> 01:22:29,741
I don't know that. You don't know that.
But if that's true,

979
01:22:29,783 --> 01:22:32,786
God bless him,
he did the right thing.

980
01:22:33,287 --> 01:22:36,957
- Damn it, Jessica, I can't just...
- Leave it alone.

981
01:22:38,083 --> 01:22:40,711
Not that I'm not happy for her.
I'm really happy for her.

982
01:22:40,711 --> 01:22:41,920
You're happy for her, right?

983
01:22:41,962 --> 01:22:44,423
- If she's happy, I'm happy.
- Right.

984
01:22:44,464 --> 01:22:47,468
- Mom, I feel stupid.
- Oh, you don't look stupid.

985
01:22:47,509 --> 01:22:48,510
You look...

986
01:22:49,636 --> 01:22:52,055
You don't look stupid.

987
01:23:09,781 --> 01:23:12,409
<i>Do you, Edward Vanderman
take Penelope Wilher</i>

988
01:23:12,409 --> 01:23:15,412
<i>to be your lawfully wedded wife?</i>

989
01:23:16,163 --> 01:23:20,000
<i>To have and to hold,</i>

990
01:23:20,834 --> 01:23:23,754
for better or for worse
for richer or for poorer

991
01:23:23,795 --> 01:23:26,256
in sickness and in health.

992
01:23:26,799 --> 01:23:30,844
To love and to cherish
from this day forward

993
01:23:31,678 --> 01:23:34,181
until death do you part?

994
01:23:37,434 --> 01:23:38,560
I do.

995
01:23:41,396 --> 01:23:44,066
And do you, Penelope Wilhern,

996
01:23:44,942 --> 01:23:47,861
take Edward Humphrey
Vanderman III

997
01:23:48,028 --> 01:23:50,781
to be your lawfully wedded husband,

998
01:23:51,490 --> 01:23:56,578
to have and to hold,
for better or for worse

999
01:23:57,204 --> 01:24:01,291
for richer or for poorer,
in sickness and in health,

1000
01:24:01,500 --> 01:24:06,088
to love and to cherish
from this day forward

1001
01:24:06,129 --> 01:24:08,590
until death do you part?

1002
01:24:35,701 --> 01:24:38,203
Nobody move!
She's fine!

1003
01:24:41,248 --> 01:24:44,251
Penelope, wait!
Penelope! Stop!

1004
01:24:45,586 --> 01:24:47,379
Look at me.

1005
01:24:47,421 --> 01:24:48,714
I am.
What is it, dear?

1006
01:24:48,755 --> 01:24:50,215
No, look at me.

1007
01:24:50,215 --> 01:24:53,927
I am! What?
I don't understand! What do you mean?

1008
01:24:55,512 --> 01:24:57,681
You... I'm sorry.

1009
01:25:02,394 --> 01:25:05,022
Penelope, it's not too late.

1010
01:25:05,105 --> 01:25:06,315
Go away, Mother!

1011
01:25:06,356 --> 01:25:08,317
<i>Honey, just think about
what you're doing.</i>

1012
01:25:08,358 --> 01:25:11,069
<i>This is the moment
we have worked so hard for.</i>

1013
01:25:11,069 --> 01:25:12,779
I said go away!

1014
01:25:12,821 --> 01:25:15,616
Sweetheart, please! Please!

1015
01:25:15,616 --> 01:25:18,785
We are one yes away
from a whole new life.

1016
01:25:18,952 --> 01:25:20,412
A whole new you!

1017
01:25:20,454 --> 01:25:22,706
But I don't want a whole new me,
Mother!

1018
01:25:22,748 --> 01:25:25,209
Sweetheart, please! Please!

1019
01:25:25,667 --> 01:25:28,462
I like myself the way I am.

1020
01:26:55,841 --> 01:26:58,135
It's not going to grow back.

1021
01:26:58,760 --> 01:27:01,889
- What makes you think I...
- I miss it too.

1022
01:27:02,306 --> 01:27:05,142
And then I remember
you're still you.

1023
01:27:13,984 --> 01:27:15,235
Oh, Penelope...

1024
01:27:16,695 --> 01:27:19,740
'One of your own kind.'
I just assumed...

1025
01:27:20,574 --> 01:27:22,284
No, we all did, Mother.

1026
01:27:22,326 --> 01:27:24,578
No, dear.
No. Don't you see?

1027
01:27:24,620 --> 01:27:27,122
I could have broken
the curse years ago

1028
01:27:27,164 --> 01:27:29,625
if I'd just done my job
as your mother,

1029
01:27:29,666 --> 01:27:31,710
and loved you as my own.

1030
01:27:31,752 --> 01:27:34,213
You didn't know.
You didn't know.

1031
01:27:50,270 --> 01:27:51,522
Oh, look.

1032
01:27:53,106 --> 01:27:56,401
You know, darling, with the
carotid artery out of the way,

1033
01:27:56,735 --> 01:28:01,532
I think a little turn up might,
right there, be sweet. Look at that.

1034
01:28:01,615 --> 01:28:04,660
What?
You're crazy.

1035
01:28:07,287 --> 01:28:10,999
Oh, it's wrong for a young woman
to want to look her best?

1036
01:28:11,041 --> 01:28:12,793
That's not a bad thing...

1037
01:28:12,876 --> 01:28:15,045
What?
I'm being her mother.

1038
01:28:15,087 --> 01:28:17,589
That's what mothers do
with daughters!

1039
01:28:17,631 --> 01:28:19,967
They talk about how
to look prettier.

1040
01:28:19,967 --> 01:28:22,469
<i>Still, I felt sad
for my mother that day...</i>

1041
01:28:22,469 --> 01:28:25,139
Why are you turning it around?
Oh, now I'm the bad guy!

1042
01:28:25,180 --> 01:28:27,808
<i>... having to cope with so many
changes all at once.</i>

1043
01:28:27,850 --> 01:28:29,810
It all went back to shit!

1044
01:28:29,852 --> 01:28:31,645
<i>I was packing to go,</i>

1045
01:28:31,645 --> 01:28:35,107
and after 25 years
with the family...

1046
01:28:35,149 --> 01:28:38,318
Jake, where are you going?
Jake, I'm talking to you. Jake?

1047
01:28:38,360 --> 01:28:40,946
And why do you have that bag?
Jake! Don't be rude!

1048
01:28:40,988 --> 01:28:43,574
You turn around when
I'm talking to you, please.

1049
01:28:43,574 --> 01:28:45,325
I happen to be...

1050
01:28:57,754 --> 01:29:01,675
There, there, now. There, there.

1051
01:29:32,956 --> 01:29:37,044
<i>But I had my own changes
to cope with,</i>

1052
01:29:38,212 --> 01:29:40,047
<i>and, while I missed the face</i>

1053
01:29:40,088 --> 01:29:41,715
<i>that had caused
so much trouble...</i>

1054
01:29:44,968 --> 01:29:47,888
<i>... the world had
moved on.</i>

1055
01:29:50,891 --> 01:29:54,478
<i>... and I was determined
to find my own way,</i>

1056
01:29:55,604 --> 01:29:58,649
<i>and determined to always
follow my heart...</i>

1057
01:29:58,649 --> 01:30:00,734
Look! My daffodil bloomed!

1058
01:30:00,734 --> 01:30:03,737
And I found
Helleborus orientalis!

1059
01:30:04,655 --> 01:30:06,448
<i>... and my conscience.</i>

1060
01:30:07,991 --> 01:30:11,328
<i>Dear Edward, that first
day in the library,</i>

1061
01:30:11,370 --> 01:30:15,374
<i>you said that you too have felt
imprisoned most of your life.</i>

1062
01:30:15,415 --> 01:30:19,378
<i>Looking back, I now believe you
were speaking from your heart.</i>

1063
01:30:19,419 --> 01:30:22,381
<i>I fear I did you a terrible
disservice that day</i>

1064
01:30:22,422 --> 01:30:25,509
<i>I knew you would run
I wanted you to,</i>

1065
01:30:25,509 --> 01:30:29,513
<i>but perhaps if I had taken
the time to really listen to you,</i>

1066
01:30:29,680 --> 01:30:32,599
<i>maybe we could have helped
each other find our way.</i>

1067
01:30:32,599 --> 01:30:37,521
<i>I'm sorry. I hope this letter
and this ring finds you well.</i>

1068
01:30:45,112 --> 01:30:50,033
Edward? Edward? Your father wants
to know what you're doing in there.

1069
01:30:53,162 --> 01:30:54,997
<i>And then came Halloween.</i>

1070
01:30:55,038 --> 01:30:56,373
Okay, everybody. We're going to start
in about ten minutes, so I need you

1071
01:30:56,415 --> 01:30:58,292
all to go and get your costumes on. OK?

1072
01:30:59,209 --> 01:31:03,797
Just get changed and line up
by the front door as quick as possible.

1073
01:31:04,089 --> 01:31:06,091
Hey! Hey! No fighting.

1074
01:31:06,175 --> 01:31:09,178
- I can be whoever I want!
- Girls, please.

1075
01:31:09,219 --> 01:31:12,139
But she knew I was
going to be Penelope.

1076
01:31:14,558 --> 01:31:18,896
All right, girls, you're going to have to
go out with the rest of the class.

1077
01:31:18,937 --> 01:31:22,900
Go and line up. Come on, line up.
Get ready to go. Come on.

1078
01:31:24,026 --> 01:31:26,820
Alice?
Honey, what's wrong?

1079
01:31:27,070 --> 01:31:31,283
Everybody's Penelope,
and I'm a stupid static cling!

1080
01:31:31,325 --> 01:31:35,496
Oh... Well, frankly,
I find you quite refreshing.

1081
01:31:35,913 --> 01:31:40,000
Come on, sweetie. Stick with me
and we'll both make it through this.

1082
01:31:42,669 --> 01:31:45,005
Trick or treat!

1083
01:31:45,005 --> 01:31:46,423
Well, hello there.

1084
01:31:47,382 --> 01:31:51,345
- I love this one. These are my favourites.
- Jess, you're going to want to see this.

1085
01:31:51,553 --> 01:31:53,639
Is this too much?

1086
01:31:57,392 --> 01:31:58,852
Bye.

1087
01:32:06,360 --> 01:32:10,447
<i>And then Wanda couldn't hold on
to the secret any longer.</i>

1088
01:32:35,556 --> 01:32:40,060
You're everywhere.
Are you freaking out or what?

1089
01:32:41,186 --> 01:32:43,897
- OK, 357.
- There it is.

1090
01:32:44,940 --> 01:32:46,316
Hold on.

1091
01:32:46,900 --> 01:32:48,402
What?

1092
01:32:49,236 --> 01:32:52,239
It's just kind of great
to see the old you.

1093
01:32:52,322 --> 01:32:54,950
- OK. All right, let's go.
- All right, here we go.

1094
01:32:56,076 --> 01:32:58,829
You can do this.
Are you ready?

1095
01:33:07,045 --> 01:33:08,839
Hi. Um... I...

1096
01:33:09,756 --> 01:33:14,011
She's gotta pee. You got a bathroom?
I'm going to get some punch.

1097
01:33:16,930 --> 01:33:21,518
Er... yeah. Yeah, sure. I guess it's OK.
Come on in.

1098
01:33:28,734 --> 01:33:30,819
<i>It looks like a good party.</i>

1099
01:33:32,488 --> 01:33:34,448
<i>Why aren't you at the party?</i>

1100
01:33:34,573 --> 01:33:36,366
I gotta pack.

1101
01:33:36,366 --> 01:33:38,202
So, are you moving?

1102
01:33:40,621 --> 01:33:45,709
Er... out-of-town job. I felt like
getting out of the city for a while.

1103
01:33:47,920 --> 01:33:50,130
<i>Away from the crowds?</i>

1104
01:33:50,631 --> 01:33:53,634
Yeah, the crowds
at the poker tables.

1105
01:33:54,301 --> 01:33:56,136
Oh, so you're a gambler?

1106
01:33:56,261 --> 01:33:59,890
Ex.
Avoiding temptation.

1107
01:34:04,728 --> 01:34:05,854
Well, that's good.

1108
01:34:07,314 --> 01:34:08,649
Good for you. I er...

1109
01:34:10,234 --> 01:34:14,488
I had a friend once
who um... liked to gamble.

1110
01:34:14,613 --> 01:34:16,865
At least, well, I heard
he liked to gamble,

1111
01:34:16,907 --> 01:34:20,244
- And, he had to stay away from...
- Take off the mask.

1112
01:34:21,912 --> 01:34:23,247
What?

1113
01:34:24,832 --> 01:34:26,291
I'm sorry.

1114
01:34:28,377 --> 01:34:30,879
All Halloween,
I've been running into...

1115
01:34:31,004 --> 01:34:37,261
well, someone I used to know.
Sorry. Ridiculous.

1116
01:34:41,723 --> 01:34:45,269
This someone,
she meant a lot to you?

1117
01:34:47,563 --> 01:34:48,522
Yes.

1118
01:34:51,316 --> 01:34:52,568
Yes, she did.

1119
01:34:54,361 --> 01:34:55,904
What happened?

1120
01:34:58,282 --> 01:35:01,118
I couldn't give her
what she wanted.

1121
01:35:01,618 --> 01:35:03,412
What did she want?

1122
01:35:07,583 --> 01:35:09,126
To be free.

1123
01:35:10,794 --> 01:35:12,171
You shit!

1124
01:35:12,212 --> 01:35:16,049
You lied to me!
I guessed piano, and you said...

1125
01:35:24,475 --> 01:35:27,728
- Penelope, I'm sorry.
- I know.

1126
01:35:27,895 --> 01:35:31,231
No. I don't have the power
to break the curse.

1127
01:35:31,982 --> 01:35:35,527
It's OK.
It turns out that I did.

1128
01:35:36,987 --> 01:35:38,447
It's me, Max.

1129
01:35:40,407 --> 01:35:42,618
My name's Johnny.

1130
01:35:43,452 --> 01:35:48,665
I know. Johnny.
I'm still me.

1131
01:36:15,275 --> 01:36:16,944
<i>So, there we were.</i>

1132
01:36:19,029 --> 01:36:21,615
<i>And we lived happily
ever after.</i>

1133
01:36:23,784 --> 01:36:27,371
Well, happily ever after
so far at least.

1134
01:36:27,538 --> 01:36:29,873
I don't get it.
What does it mean?

1135
01:36:30,290 --> 01:36:34,211
- Well, what do you think it means?
- Rich people suck!

1136
01:36:34,628 --> 01:36:37,047
It's always the mother's fault.

1137
01:36:38,382 --> 01:36:40,259
We're all cursed?

1138
01:36:40,300 --> 01:36:44,138
It's not the power of the curse,
it's the power you give the curse.

1139
01:36:44,179 --> 01:36:47,474
- What did you say, Shrimp?
- He's not a shrimp, dummy.

1140
01:36:47,558 --> 01:36:50,477
- He is too a shrimp!
- Hey! That's not nice!

1141
01:36:51,311 --> 01:36:52,980
That's very good, Billy.

1142
01:36:53,814 --> 01:36:57,401
OK, they're serving snacks
down at the picnic tables.

1143
01:36:57,401 --> 01:36:59,570
Then, after break,
we'll go explore,

1144
01:36:59,611 --> 01:37:01,864
and see what you can collect.

1145
01:37:05,617 --> 01:37:07,411
Stay together.

